European inflation slipped into food
Accelerated inflation in the euro area is primarily due to the dizzying rise in food prices.
The increase in prices in November has been higher than expected in the 13 countries of the euro area, registering - after 2.6 percent in October - an annual inflation of 3.1 percent, announced the Statistical Office of the Union based in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts were only likely at 3 percent, Bloomberg said.
The European Central Bank (ECB), unlike the US, British and Canadian issuing banks, did not cut basic interest, on the pretext that the decline, along with rising commodity prices and reduced forced unemployment, would provoke a spiral of inflation.
The ECB wants to keep the inflation rate below, but at least close to two percent.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in trap 22: "we have to negotiate" on inflation so that later it does not have to intervene in this issue.
Inflation of 3.3 percent, recorded in Germany, broke the twelve-year record; while in Spain it rose from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
Inflation surged in the euro area as a result of galloping food and energy prices.
Wheat forwards rose 88 percent and soybean prices reached their highest level since 1973.
Similarly, much more had to be paid in 2007 for vegetable oil and dairy products.
The price of crude oil on the world market rose this year by 52 percent, reaching nearly $100 a barrel last month.
According to the ECB, inflation in 2008 will jump from the current 2.1 percent to 2.5 percent, while by 2009 it will already fall to 1.9 percent.
According to analysts, annual inflation will remain in the next 3 or 4 months around 3 percent, however the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, the ECB is expected to cut interest rates twice in 2008.
Gallup predicts a government crisis
After a long stalemate, by early December support for the Alliance of Young Democrats had risen significantly, reaching its highest level since 2002, while Gallup had never before experienced such a low level – 13 percent – in the case of socialists.
The difference in the case of secure party voters - due to the greater firmness of the opposition voters - would mean a support of more than two-thirds (71 percent) versus a support of one-fifth for the socialists (20 percent).
According to the poll, the Democratic Forum and the Alliance of Free Democrats would not reach even the limit necessary to have some parliamentary seat: their support within the entire population is two percent.
Among the secure voters there are one percent more supporters on both sides.
The economic environment continued to deteriorate even compared to the previous low - it has never been higher, 41 percent the proportion of those who judged the country's economic situation especially bad, while another 46 percent believe the situation is quite bad.
Families, after the most hopeful expectations of spring and summer, are now more pessimistic about changing their own economic situation.
As far as next year is concerned, the majority of the population is experiencing a deterioration of the situation and only a tenth expect an improvement.
In December, 71 percent of respondents, higher than any previous Gallup poll, said the prime minister is doing poorly than good.
Thirteen percent of respondents trust or trust Ferenc Gyurcsány very much, while Viktor Orbán has the support of 38 percent of respondents.
54 percent of the population does not trust the head of government at all and 27 percent does not trust the president of the Alliance of Young Democrats.
One of the indicators of the configuration of the political situation is that, what proportion of society thinks it is possible to control the discontent experienced in front of the person of the Head of Government without a change of government.
While after the October riots last year 35 percent thought it would be desirable to keep the government and the head of government in power, today this proportion is only 20 percent, while the relative majority (33 percent) believes that the only solution is to hold new elections.
Interest in the referendum is characterized by the fact that 60 percent of respondents to the participation question responded that it would surely participate and another 20 percent said it is likely to participate.
By comparison, in "a general election to be held this Sunday" would surely participate only 55 percent of the population and another 15 percent believe likely to participate. Based on the current intentions of the voters there is no doubt about the result of the popular consultation.
Seventy-four percent of the population would disapprove of the payment of tuition fees, 79 percent of the medical consultation service, and 84 percent of hospital care.
If we look at these proportions only among the safe participants in the referendum, 81, 84 and 89 percent of voters would reject the introduction of study fees, payment for medical consultations and hospital care.
The most expensive is the Auchan, the Tesco has quintupled its prices
The average price level increase of 16 percent was maintained by the hypermarkets of the Budaörs gold trading triangle, with the difference that this year VAT has not been increased.
Article by Napi Gazdaság
This year also increased by an average of 16 percent in the gold trading triangle of Budaörs the usual Christmas basket of the newspaper Napi, but in all hypermarkets there was a growth well above the thousand HUF.
As in December last year prices had already been "fired" in grocery stores, so there was no drastic percentage increase compared to the high starting point.
However, it is evidently frightening for consumers that what they were able to buy last year at a price well below nine thousand HUF, today they cannot do it even for ten thousand.
The basket of Napi in the hypermarkets studied exceeded with a minimum of 91 HUF the psychological limit of ten thousand HUF.
And the highest value basket was 10,573 HUF.
(In 2003, that basket cost HUF 6800.)
The price of Unicum liquor and fish remained almost at the level of the previous year, but there was a sharp increase in turkey breast fillet, walnut and poppy seed.
The price of wheat flour and bread followed the data of the Central Bureau of Statistics, although in Auchan we have also found a kilogram of bread for the price of 139 HUF.
The competition did not reduce the price of the product to less than 200 HUF.
It was also surprising in this store that the price of the Coca-Cola with two-liter redeemable bottle cost less than 200 HUF, so that this product, even with the price of the bottle, cost only 257 HUF.
However, in the basket of Napi Auchan was the most expensive, while Cora the cheapest.
According to our calculations, with respect to Christmas prices last year, Cora rose by 15, while Tesco and Auchan with about 18 percent the prices listed in the Napi basket.
Comparing last year’s most expensive basket with this year’s cheapest basket, the difference has been 12 percent, while growth between last year’s cheapest and this year’s most expensive has been 21 percent.
The average growth was 1480 HUF.
Last year the average price growth was HUF 1206, so that during Christmas last year in prices we felt the increase in VAT.
It was precisely this process that destroyed trade, the supermarkets were visibly unable to decide on the price margin to apply for each product and to calculate the effect of the change in prices on consumption.
(If the trader misplans the speed of a product’s circulation, he may lose a significant profit on the margin that adjusts to the volume of sales.)
The increase in the price of the Napi basket reached such extremes as a result of the increase in VAT, that the most expensive was higher with 1720 HUF to the value recorded in 2006, while in the cheapest the difference was only 844 HUF.
This year there were no such extremes, since the highest price now has been 1630 HUF more than last year and the cheapest also increased with 1284 HUF.
Comparing the two holiday seasons, there was a catastrophic growth in prices in less than 20 months, in hypermarkets the price of consumer goods of first necessity grew more than 30 percent.
(However this does not necessarily confirm the figures of the Central Bureau of Statistics: this office, in the case of some staple foods registered in the 12-month interval a price increase of more than 30 percent.
So for example, in addition to wheat, also in the case of egg.)
According to the Napi basket, in the latter case this seems almost impossible, because in the price of this product that was quite expensive already last year compared to the base, there was, in the worst case, only a 10 percent increase in prices.
According to all the indices, the suppliers of flour have a stronger position than those of egg, being able to impose the drastic increase in prices even to multinationals.
Hypermarkets do not complain in the golden trading triangle, they constantly talk about positive results.
According to our experiences, most consumers of the three stores visited are no longer interested in prices.
Of all the products they buy large quantities, taking by pallets the preserved foods.
On Wednesday morning, large queues were formed in front of the boxes because the number of customers suddenly increased.
However, we have information that inside the country sales volumes are lower, many multinationals complain to survey institutes because the revenues are below their plans and not only in the case of food, but also in that of appliances.
In many hospitals it is saved with disinfectants
This year, several thousand infections have been recorded in hospitals, primarily caused by the misapplication of antibiotics.
The hygiene conditions in hospitals, the overcrowding of beds and the overloading of staff do not favor infection control, says the chief medical officer of the National Center for Epidemiology.
In many hospitals, even disinfectants are saved.
Not long ago, an MRSA infection was diagnosed in the traumatology department of János Hospital.
In a man hospitalized after a serious accident, the presence of antibiotic-resistant bacteria was detected.
The patient was isolated.
The same type of contagion occurred in this same hospital earlier this year.
A man injured in a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital and the same patient soon after had to return to the hospital as a result of the contagion with MRSA and since then it has not been possible to perform a major surgical intervention due to the presence of the bacteria in his organism.
As of December 10 this year, 1,094 cases of hospital infection caused by multidrug-resistant agents have been registered in the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System, said Karolina Böröcz, department head of the National Center for Epidemiology.
This means that in hospitals this number of infections produced by multidrug-resistant agents has certainly been recorded, of the rest there is no information.
About two-thirds of infections (683 cases) are due to MRSA, i.e. methicillin-oxacillin resistant Staphylococcus aureus.
One-third of humans carry Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their noses without causing disease.
Infections caused by SA (e.g., inflammation of the throat, tonsillitis, skin infections, wound infections) react well to antibiotics and are easy to treat.
However, once it is over- or improperly applied to antibiotics, bacteria that normally react well to antibiotics transform into highly antibiotic-resistant bacteria and quickly spread in inadequate hospital conditions.
They can cause serious hospital infections, e.g. wound infections or sepsis primarily in patients with transient or chronic immunodeficiency, in patients with the weakened organism, in the elderly or in people with low weight.
In the opinion of the doctor-director of the Hospital János there is nothing special in the infection of MRSA, these infections are daily in hospitals.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, MRSA is only absent - said Tibor Nyulasi - where its presence is not examined.
Resistant to antibiotics
"These patients are isolated, nurses attend to them in rubber gloves and masks and there are the right antibiotics for their treatment," said Tibor Nyulasi.
Hospitalized patients are pre-examined for the presence of MRSA in their body, but even so infection cannot be prevented in all cases.
It is not fashionable to take samples
It would be possible to prevent hospital MRSA infections in most cases, however the current national hospital circumstances do not favor the prevention of formation and contagion with multidrug-resistant pathogens - says Karolina Böröcz.
Because this infection occurs primarily in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should screen hospitalized patients and immediately isolate patients who carry MRSA in their bodies.
However, microbiological sampling is not fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
This is also due to the fact that the National Health Fund does not finance these medical examinations.
So most cases come to light when MRSA infections are already visible in the patient," said the doctor-head of the epidemiological center's department.
The European Union makes rigorous recommendations for the application of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also national directives for the treatment of infections and disease.
Antibiotic therapy should be targeted, i.e. microbiological tests should be done to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always meet this requirement.
Microbiological sampling is even less common in the case of walking patients or in basic care,” said Karolina Böröcz.
Save money with disinfectants
Scientific experiments have shown that in most cases MRSA is transmitted from one patient to another through healthcare personnel.
Therefore, hand washing, the use of rubber gloves and masks play a very important role, however also in this sense considerable faults are experienced in hospitals.
MRSA is transmitted through drop transmission and direct contact between people, however in national hospital circumstances it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
What’s more, hospital rooms are often crowded, beds are often very close together, although to prevent the epidemic, patients should be separated by at least a distance of 1.5 meters.
Unfortunately you can also experience - added Karolina Böröcz - that in less favourable economic hospitals you save with disinfectants, there are few nurses and many patients and therefore there is a greater likelihood of infection.
In the opinion of Karolina Böröcz, where appropriate preventive measures are implemented, fewer infections of this type are recorded or the contagion of the pathogen can be stopped.
Government Program Against MRSA
Treatment of MRSA infection is a huge expense for the National Health Insurance Fund, so it is fought against in all countries.
In England, for example, there is a government program to prevent and reduce MRSA cases.
Apparently the program is successful, according to the data provided, MRSA infections show a declining trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has among its priorities the prevention of multidrug-resistant agents (among them MRSA) and hospital infections due to these pathogens.
Negative blood alcohol control of police commander who caused a fatal accident
The official expert report on the case of the fatal accident caused by the commander of the police of district XXII has been made.
The possibility that he was driving drunk or in a stunned state can be excluded the since resigned commander of the police of the XXII district, who on Tuesday ran over and caused the death of a passer-by, said Attila Morvai, spokesman for the Attorney General's Office of the Capital, after the expert report on the case had been prepared.
The expert report confirmed the result of the primary blood alcohol control that had already found that the former police commander did not consume alcoholic beverages before putting himself behind the wheel.
The head of the police station of the XXII district on Tuesday with his private vehicle as he turned to Kossuth Lajos Street of the XXII district ran over a 55-year-old man, who intended to cross the street, but not in the area designated for pedestrians.
(The latter fact, that is, the pedestrian did not use the zebra to cross the street, according to the regulations of the Traffic Code are not extenuating circumstances, the driver must always give way when bending.)
The passerby lost his life after being hospitalized.
The district police officer resigned and requested his retirement, according to the police statement, because he was very moved by the case.
The investigation of the case is carried out by the Budapest Public Prosecutor’s Office.
Attila Morvai also said the former police commander had initially collaborated with prosecutors in charge of the investigation.
