Bulgaria, the EU’s real estate paradise
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is admirable - the attention of the whole of Europe is directed towards that previously mentioned Balkan country.
What thing, where and who buy in the even cheaper EU market, will quickly become more expensive?
Analysis of the Bulgarian division of Re/Max.
The preferred target for real estate acquisitions in Eastern Europe is undoubtedly Bulgaria, with its cheap apartments of the ski slopes and the chalets of the beaches.
The mountainous regions of Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa are the most preferred, while on the beaches Albena, the "Golden Coast", the "Sun Coast", the ancient Sozopol and Nesebar, but more and more people are looking for real estate also in the surroundings of Kavarna and Balchik.
According to the analysts of Re/Max in Bulgaria, sooner or later also the central area of the country - such as Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna - will arouse the interest of real estate developers and more and more people will buy real estate in the especially cheap area of Rus.
In the same way, the capital Sofia can be attractive, the commercial and office spaces promise a rapid recovery of the investment.
Bulgaria is on the best path to becoming one of the most attractive golf paradises in Europe, and can thus be a prominent destination also during the other two seasons, in addition to summer and winter.
Therefore, cautious investors are already making their purchases, for example in the surroundings of Bansko.
In the opinion of analysts, those who buy real estate in Bulgaria are also striving to change their lives and their way of life.
Most of the customers are English, but they also come from France, Belgium, Spain and increasingly from Romania.
Also present are the Maltese and Cypriot promoters and traditionally there are many Russian customers on the Black Sea beaches and in the ski paradises.
Foreign customers can be classified into three groups - says Georgi Jankov, Regional Director of Re/Max in Bulgaria.
Those who intend to settle here buy new or renovated properties for a price between 50 and 100,000 euros or old houses in poor condition between 5 and 15,000 euros, to renovate them later.
They require good communication and access, also for them is important the proximity of a big city, shops and usually a local doctor.
They constitute the second category of chalet buyers (Bulgaria in December was included in the top 10 holiday destinations of the Germans).
The third group are real estate investors who make their purchases in the hope of benefiting in the medium or long term.
The price of capital real estate is constantly increasing, since the demand is increasing.
Although Bulgaria has the lowest property prices in the European Union, in the last five years they have experienced an annual increase of 21 percent.
The increase in the price of real estate considerably outweighs the growth in wages.
Fodor and the Six by Hundred Hungarians
As reported by the Minister of Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor the expert level meetings will end on Tuesday and on Wednesday after the official inauguration will continue negotiations at ministerial level on the post-2012 international climate regime.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world are deliberating on the Bali Roadmap on post-Kyoto emission reduction efforts until 2012.
There are now lively discussions between developing and industrialized countries on this issue.
The United States has already indicated that for the moment it does not want to negotiate on precise figures, although it tends to reach an agreement that, compared to the situation of 1990, by the year 2020 the emission of gases responsible for the greenhouse effect will decrease by 25 to 40 percent.
Another major theme of the conference is whether or not industrialized countries, in addition to reducing emissions, are willing to offer material and technological aid to countries in need.
An agreement was also reached on aid to be offered to developing countries.
The support fund, foreseen in the Kyoto Protocol, will be led by a 16-member board of directors, probably within the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF), writes the "Piac és Profit".
The Six by Hundreds of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, Minister for Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor supports the EU's efforts to retain its leading role in global climate protection and promote the signing of the new international agreement until 2009.
The minister stated that the EU is committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 percent by 2020 from the 1990 level, regardless of whether or not the “post-2012 agreement” will be signed, and is willing to commit to decreasing even 30 percent if the other major developed regions of the world and developing countries are also willing to make commitments in line with their responsibility and capabilities.
Gábor Fodor pointed out that the signatory countries of the 1997 Kyoto Protocol committed to decrease by 5.2 percent, within this the then 15 EU member states committed to meet an 8 percent decrease.
Hungary’s commitment is to reduce by 6 percent the emission of greenhouse gases with respect to the period between 1985 and 1987, which our country will comply with – says the press release of the Ministry of Environment.
There is a lot at stake in Bali, since in two years the international agreement on long-term climate policy will have to be signed, because otherwise, it is certain that its entry into force would be postponed until after 2012. In this case the UN Nobel Peace Prize reduction commitments, assumed in the Kyoto Protocol would not be immediately followed by a new international system of reduction of emissions, whose need was noticed in its latest report by the IPCC.
With this, the reduction of emissions would suffer a delay and could not prevent an increase of more than 2 ° C of the average temperature of the Earth, a fact that according to scientists would have immeasurable and irreversible consequences.
British army recruits on YouTube
British army units at a video distributor publish footage of actions filmed in Iraq and Afghanistan to popularize themselves.
First the British Air Force (RAD) took advantage of YouTube services: special units deployed in Afghanistan since March 2006 are uploading videos about their actions against the Taliban, the BBC reported.
These recordings made with mini cameras mounted on the helmets are checked in Kandahar’s general body of operations, then sent to London to be uploaded to the Internet.
The political message is inevitable.
There are already 139 recordings from air force soldiers that have been uploaded in this way to the Internet and its "channel" has already been seen by more than 75,000 people.
The British Ministry of Defence registered in the spring of 2007 under the name of "defence headquarters" and publishes videos of both actions perpetrated in Iraq and Afghanistan, while the Commonwealth Office and the multinational forces in Iraq (MNFI) have their own YouTube channel.
Operation in Afghanistan
Originally the air force had uploaded the videos for recruitment purposes, but in the opinion of the Ministry of Defense they also serve to present to the public the true objective of the presence of the British army abroad.
This kind of propaganda costs practically nothing compared to conventional recruitment television spots, defence expert Gordon Mackenzie told the BBC, but inevitably has some political message, since in a specific way they justify the raison d'être of the military actions decided by the government.
The Americans made a video game.
The army is also concerned about the fact that, in addition to the suspiciously edited and censored recordings, amateur videos also appear in the distributor, for example about the death of the soldiers: in the "official" propaganda films, a bit hypocritical, the officers talk at most about losses, without however presenting the bloody part of the fights.
In addition, the battlefields of Iraq and Afghanistan have been uploaded to the Internet and numerous videos recorded in real operations, but the British army is only lately taking advantage of this opportunity.
Americans use a slightly different form of recruitment with freely downloadable shooter video games called America's Army, in which in the midst of a more or less real situation the player can stand directly in place of the soldiers.
