The party is not always written with red numbers
In Hungary the law defines precisely the days that are written with red numbers on the calendar and it has already become a widespread practice that around the holidays - that next year will be less - workdays are reorganized.
Even in the EU or North America, holidays are not unitary.
Hungarian laws make a difference between a national holiday, a state holiday and holidays.
The festive days are mainly related to religious festivals and historical ephemeris.
We also celebrate the New Year: both the last day of the old year, and the first day of the new year is a holiday - the latter above all so that those who spent celebrating the old year can rest.
Throughout the year we have eleven holidays written with red numbers on the calendar.
It is a national holiday on March 15 in memory of the revolution of 1848 and October 23, commemorating the revolution of 1956.
On August 20 we celebrate the founding of the State, on May 1st the Feast of Labor, on November 1st and 2nd we remember our deceased relatives and friends.
In addition, in our country are two-day feasts Easter, Pentecost and Christmas.
According to the calendar, our state, national or religious holidays rarely coincide with a weekend, so it is often bridged when there is only one working day before or after the holiday.
In exchange for the extended weekends, during the previous Saturdays you can not be absent from work or school.
It is the minister of labor who regulates in his specific decree when it is necessary to work exactly in exchange for the day directly preceding or following the feast.
This legal rule is mandatory for all employers and their employees, as well as for employees and civil servants.
It is not compulsory for companies and service institutions that, due to their function, work uninterruptedly even during holidays.
This year the order of work can be altered only around the holidays of the year: from December 24 practically stops life in the country, because according to experiences, most people "bridge" during the days between Christmas and the end of the year or take their holidays during these days.
Next year several of our holidays will coincide with midday or weekends, so there will be fewer changes in working days than this year.
First the agenda will be modified around the Labor Day so that then, for four successive days, workers can rest.
Saturday, April 26 will be a working day, so that in return Friday, May 2 will be a holiday.
The other change relates to the holiday of October 23: Saturday, October 18, will have to work instead of Friday, October 24.
On the other hand, next year during the end of the year party you can rest, since from December 24 you will not work almost anywhere, even if the last day of the year is a Wednesday.
Six small deterrents to make your colleagues’ lives bitter
Emails we forget to send, sound messages we never receive, innocent lies that happen to us without realizing it: all of them are part of our daily folklore at work.
You have to decide whether to adapt to small discomforts or consciously avoid confusing situations that can irritate others.
Advice.
“I’m sorry, I forgot to tell you that you’ve been searched for in the marketing department,” says one of your colleagues.
That's why you didn't go on a date?
At best he feels it and tries to fix the issue, maybe call the marketing department to tell them that he forgot to deliver the message (this is the less usual solution).
Most of the time the issue is resolved by apologizing.
Before proceeding to embarrassing explanations, it is worth meditating on the things with which you can make your colleagues’ lives bitter and consciously endeavor to avoid them.
Do you borrow something that is not yours?
There’s nothing more irritating than when you want to pick up a document, office supplies or your phone and you can’t find them.
Remember yesterday you put the stapler on the table, but by this morning it disappeared?
Do you find your lost pen on the desk of one of your colleagues?
Do not take anything away from your colleagues without asking them, because they will rightly be angry with you for stealing their things.
Do not pick up envelopes or post-it from the office because it can be unpleasant when you need them immediately and they run out before time.
Do you gossip about the private lives of your colleagues?
There is no good solution to stop rumors that are already running.
Who, what is he doing and with whom?
Where and why?
Don’t pass on to everyone the information (conjectures) you have about the private lives of your colleagues!
Don’t abuse your colleague’s trust when he shares his most intimate secrets with you!
Bury in yourself what you have heard and do not gossip about your colleague in his absence, although others also know the things about him.
Are you going on sick leave unjustifiably?
When you call the office on the phone and say that you are sick and your head hurts unbearably, you feel bad or good, you feel that that day you prefer to rest; think that others must do your work, your indispensible tasks, your work by term.
Don't bother your colleague!
If you already know in advance that the next day you will not go to the office or something may happen to you, so you should stay at home, let them know, so that your colleagues or your boss do not have to confront you the next day.
Tinnitus, laughter, phone calls
Are you involved in your work, but are you abruptly pulled out of it by your colleagues?
Have you involuntarily heard a phone conversation that would have been better not to hear?
Don’t bother your colleagues with your rattles, singing, conversations aloud (except when you do them above their head), patting, constant blasphemies, expressing your discontents aloud.
All of these can be annoying, even if they are not delving into a project right now (writing, planning, organizing).
Do you blame others for a mistake?
Don’t blame others if you haven’t finished something in time, forgot to send an important letter or message!
You don’t allude to the chaos eventually reigning in the office, nor to the noise your colleagues make!
You must acknowledge if you have made a mistake that harms others and you must repair the fault!
Ask how you can repair your fault!
Do you feel too much at home in the office?
Jogging and slippers: very comfortable habit for the house, but not suitable for the office!
Don’t wear comfortable jogging even if your occupation allows it!
Don’t be distracted, respect your colleagues and yourself by wearing everyday, elegant and beautiful clothes when your occupation demands it!
