Banks want to solve the crisis
The US Federal Reserve Bank, the European Central Bank and the British, Swiss and Canadian Central Banks decided to fight together against the crisis of the finance market.
Over one hundred billion dollars will be received through tenders in the Monetary Marking.
In these tenders the banks auction the interest rates for which they are able to lend money.
For example, the U.S. Fed will send out $40 billion to bid, and then another $24 billion will be provided by the central banks of Europe and Switzerland.
After the September 11 attacks, it is the first time that central banks from different states have agreed on this coordinated process to protect and mitigate the consequences of the financial crisis.
"This step should solve the biggest economic problem, namely the continued growth of the shortage of free capital that banks could lend," Bernard Baumohl of the consulting firm Economic Outlook Group wrote in his report to clients.
“This coordinated action by the central banks likely lowered the recession in the United States from 65 percent to fifty percent,” Baumohl added in his report.
Banks have already spent $60 billion on unpaid loans, mostly in the United States.
Economists still expect billions in losses.
“Central banks should really be afraid of what awaits them when they decide to take this step,” said Kieran Davies, chief economist at ABN Amro.
“It seems that the situation is really bad,” he added.
Central banks fear that they will have the same problems with access to loans and therefore will have to lend more expensive to their customers.
This would reduce consumption and send the American economy into recession with different impacts on the growth of the world economy.
The central banks thus decided, after failing to reduce the so-called LIBOR rate, the London interbank rate used for lending money in the interbank market.
This means that banks were constantly afraid to lend themselves money even as the Central Banks of the US, Canada and Britain lowered their interest rates several times during the autumn.
"It will have the same effect as another interest rate drop," Tempus Consulting's Greg Salvaggio told Reuters.
Some economists are not surprised that the step taken by the central banks contributes to igniting the crisis because it does not solve the fundamental problem that is the fall of the real estate market in the United States.
