New fears about gas between Russia and Ukraine
The growing dispute over the price of gas between Ukraine and Russia, increases the risk that it will affect the export of the fuel to Western Europe by Russia.
Most of the gas exported by Russia to the European Union (EU) is directed through Ukraine, so every friction between the two nations is a source of attention.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow raises the price of gas, Russia will have to pay higher transit fees.
An earlier dispute last year reduced supplies to EU states.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow came with the Ukrainian government and the Russian state, the monopoly owner of the gas, Gazprom, trying to agree on how much money Ukraine was to pay for Russian gas in 2008.
Gazprom said it would charge Ukraine more, as it has pledged to pay an extra 50% in 2008 for gas coming from neighboring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say it could be that Ukraine pays 40 percent more for Gazprom’s imports.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important transits for gas during the talks," Ukrainian Economy Minister Anatoly Kinakh told Reuters news agency.
“The changes in gas prices should not relate to our arguments about the levels of transit rates [to Western Europe] via Ukraine.”
The last major gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev, Gazprom cut supplies to Ukraine in January 2006.
This meant a drop in exports to Western Europe, which quickly raised prices.
Russian gas accounts for a quarter of the EU’s supply.
Russia has the largest gas reserves in the world, but much of it is not yet fully developed.
As a result, Gazprom supplements its own supply with gas from Turkmenistan and other former Soviet Central Asian nations.
The NHS will have to prove foreign workers.
The Scottish NHS needs to check the criminal records of employees outside of Europe, one guard said.
Auditor General Robert Black’s recommendation came after a foreign doctor was found to be linked to the Glasgow airport attack in June.
Black also expressed concern that the Scottish NHS has no idea exactly how many foreign personnel it has.
However, his report pointed to other checks being carried out correctly through a sample of five health authorities.
The auditor general checked the number of foreign staff hired outside the European Economic Area in the wake of the attacks on Glasgow airport.
Bilal Abdullah, 28, an Iraqi doctor at the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after crashing a jeep into the gates of the airport’s terminal building.
He was one of three doctors who performed at the Old Bailey by video conference in October, charged in connection with the alleged car bombings in Britain.
NHS expects to conduct pre-employment checks on candidates, to ensure they meet the qualifications, experience and authorization to work in the UK.
Although the Scottish Health Board uses “Disclosure Scotland” to conduct criminal background checks, the agency has no jurisdiction to obtain this information outside of Britain.
The auditor general’s report recommends, among other measures, that boards should be guided by the Criminal Records Bureau, which helps employers with criminal controls in many countries outside Britain.
“While we found some of the personal records with evidence of these controls, this is not a routine review,” the report says.
Black states that the Scottish NHS has a high level of compliance with its own employment policies, but notes that: "our report highlights areas that can be improved to ensure that the necessary information is available on the number of NHS foreign personnel."
BMA Scotland President Dr Peter Terry said it was “highly unlikely” that pre-employment checks could identify potential NHS employees who might commit terrorist acts in the future.
“The report suggests that pre-employment check-ups work in NHS Scotland but it is unclear what the added value of the recommendations made is,” he explained.
Scottish health authorities say they currently have 1,161 foreigners, most of them doctors and nurses.
But the auditor general warned that the number may be higher, in part because boards have trouble identifying which employees have indefinite residence permits.
The investigation also found that verification procedures established by NHS authorities in Ayrshire and Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire and Lothian were being widely complied with.
This includes passport checks, work permits and qualification checks.
The Scottish government is currently reviewing the policy and pre-employment guide for foreigners in the NHS.
Health Secretary Nicola Sturgeon said: “It was of great interest that this work was carried out in the wake of the terrorist attack on Glasgow Airport.
He added that the Scottish government, in conjunction with the health boards, could consider the recommendations of the reports and that this will be reflected in the update of the pre-employment control guidelines for all working groups — including foreigners — which they planned to release next month.
