Is the subprime mortgage crisis infecting the American credit card market?
When there is blood in the water, it is natural for dorsal fins to swim excitedly around.
Today, with the U.S. housing market in crisis, predators have their eyes on the U.S. credit card market.
Analysts at Goldman Sachs estimate that credit card losses could reach $99 million if the subprime mortgage crisis spreads to other forms of consumer credit.
Signs of contagion are already visible.
There is an increase in both card charges and crime rates, which measures the proportion of balances that have not been amortized or that are more than 30 days late respectively.
HSBC announced last month that it has taken a $1.4 million charge in its U.S. consumer finance business, in part due to the weakness of card borrowers.
However, it is too early for panic.
Delinquency and delinquency are at low levels.
According to Moody’s, a ratings agency, the third quarter crime rate of 3.89% was almost one percentage point below the historical average.
The deterioration in rates can be explained in part by technical factors.
A change in the American People’s Bankruptcy Act (2005) resulted in a sharp drop in bankruptcy applications, which in turn represent a large loss on credit cards; the number of applications (and therefore, of default) would be growing again, or it may happen that conditions for borrowers were worsening.
The industry also reports solid payout rates, which show how much of its debt consumers pay each month.
And confidence in credit cards and asset-backed securities is quite firm, despite paralysis in other financial areas.
Dennis Moroney of TowerGroup, a research firm, predicts that emission volumes for 2007 will be about 25% higher than last year.
The direct channels of crisis infection between subprime mortgages and the credit card market certainly exist: consumers like to charge debts to credit cards now that lenders are out of date.
But credit card issuers look more at liquidity flow than asset values, so falling prices don’t necessarily trigger a change in borrowers’ creditworthiness.
They can even work to outperform the issuers.
The incentives for consumers to continue amortizing the mortgage decreases if the properties are worth less than the loan value; and as a result, the payment of the card debt rises on the list of priorities.
Card issuers can also respond quickly and flexibly to the difficult conditions that mortgage lenders face by changing interest rates or altering credit balances.
That in theory should reduce the risk of rapid asset retaliation.
“We’re not going to wake up one day and re-evaluate all the loans,” says Gary Perlin, head of finance at Capital One.
If a sudden subprime infection in the credit card market is unlikely, the risks of a sustained decline are much more real.
If home prices are lower and a credit contraction pushes America into recession, the industry undoubtedly faces a harsher future.
Those dorsal fins must continue to be monitored.
