Venus: Earth's twin brother.
Although its atmosphere is not suitable for life, Venus is the most Earth-like planet, something that until now had not been posed. The European probe "Venus Express" discovered rays in the atmosphere and whirlpools at the poles, the same that appear also in winter on Earth.
For three decades, researchers had suspected that there might be lightning on Venus.
But now the European probe has brought new evidence: it discovered electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere. On Venus the rays are silent from a height of 54 kilometers from one cloud and behind another, says Cris Russell of the University of California in Los Angeles to the scientific journal "Nature".
According to the famous Urey-Miller model of the origin of life, lightning caused life on Earth: storms may have provoked reactions in the ocean that, in turn, would have given rise to the amino acids that are the basic components of life.
On Venus it’s not like that: if there ever was life there, that would have to be in one of the earliest states of evolution,” explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today, on the surface of Venus there can be no life: the atmospheric pressure is almost 100 times higher than on Earth and on the surface temperatures of 500 ° C reign, oscillating in such a way that temperatures below zero can be reached.
“Possibly, Venus is a ‘diabolical’ Earth twin, but it’s still a twin,” Russell said.
The main goal of the Venus Express mission is to answer the question of why Venus, so Earth-like in mass and size, has evolved so differently.
Since since the 1990s there were no special missions, only for research of this planet, the launch of "Venus-Express" in November 2005 was a very important step for Venus research.
The latest research results to be presented in many Nature papers, according to the researchers, underscore not only the uniqueness of Venus in the Solar System.
"This also demonstrates that neighboring planets have more common features with Earth than we had assumed," ESA reports.
Despite the already known stormy winds at the North Pole, the researchers discovered in the south polar region also a vortex formed by the clouds that rotates faster.
This phenomenon is reminiscent of wind flows in the high atmospheric layers of the Earth’s poles, according to a team of researchers led by Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Institute of Special Astrophysics and Space Physics.
The second planet of the Solar System has the mass almost equal to the Earth and with its equatorial diameter of 12,000 kilometers it is almost as large.
This planet also called dawn star or evening star orbits the Sun nearly 225 days.
But its rotation period is slower: one day on Venus equals 243 days on Earth.
Although Venus with its surface temperatures of 460 degrees and atmospheric pressure of 92 bar does not resemble Earth much, scientists start from the basis that both planets had formed under the same conditions.
The two planets had agglomerated water that on Earth remained in the oceans, but on Venus it dissociated into the universe.
While on Earth carbon dioxide had turned into carbon stones, on Venus it forms most of the atmosphere.
