Richard Gere only lacks more cynicism.
The two films "The Hunting Party" and "Moerderischer Frieden" are again devoted to the war in the Balkans.
But the two weren’t very convinced.
Either the concepts are fixed a lot on actions and shootings or the two movies are too exciting.
Richard Gere with his "The Hunting Party" can't help in this case either.
At first there was good news: Karadzic and Mladic, the war criminals, continue to hide in the Balkan Mountains, but it was precisely there, in the dark interior of the country during the Bosnian war, that actor Richard Gere was discovered again.
We had finally lost sight of the most handsome man of the eighties, because no one wanted to see him after his pleasant and unimportant roles in women’s movies and after many press conferences on Buddhism.
Now, all of a sudden, Richard Gere is the most important plot to perhaps watch the movie "The Hunting Party- when a hunter becomes what he pursues" (Why do movie titles nowadays have to be so long and silly?).
The film has a wonderful presentation for the eye: in the background, his role as a reporter in the war is the presentation of what Richard Gere could do, if fate and the film industry had not been so merciful to him. He was a man whose best times of life have already passed, who as a monument to the ruin of his decadence retained until now most of his charm.
"The Hunting Party", despite this triumph, along with "Moerderischer Frieden" which is the German production and will also be presented this week, turn out to be just a series of unsuccessful films about the war in the Balkans.
The film "Moerderischer Frieden" can be narrated in a nutshell: it is about two German soldiers in Kosovo (Adrian Topol, Max Riemelt) who want to save a Serbian from the Kosovo snipers, one of them acts very quickly and that also leads him to fall in love with her.
The meaning of the film is lost by the actions and the shootings, although we celebrate that the Serbs are not presented once again as the only culprits.
The film is like the German series "Alarm fuer Cobra 11" without a highway, but in a war situation.
In the example of "The Hunting Party" you can investigate, because in reality there was never a good film about the war in the Balkans.
At another time, with another director and another screenwriter (Richard Shepard on two counts), the story about American reporters in the war who go to detect a Serbian war criminal named “fox” could probably be a new “Apocalypse Now.”
Thus, the stories are surprisingly similar: the small teams go twice to the mountain to carry out something that the army can not do and each time it turns out a trip in madness.
One reason for the failure of “The Hunting Party” is when they first introduce us to Simon Hunt, who is not allowed to be simply a cynic with a heart.
No, the script also foresees a love affair with a Bosnian Muslim that they will kill later.
Then “The Hunting Party” is far from reality, especially when in the last five minutes the reporters with an impressive speed achieve what NATO, the CIA and all the headhunters of the world could not achieve for five years, which was to capture the war criminal and leave the Bosnian Muslims to take revenge in a fair way.
It is so bad, that they make you want to appeal to the international court in The Hague based on crimes against cinematic logic.
